<br>
<br>
     There is no point in building a capsule, or worse, a mini-spaceplane when the shuttle is to be fast tracked to go to service ISS anyway. The Delta IV heavy class PROTON launch vehicle could at best lob a rump Soyuz in a circumlunar mission. This was the ZOND series, and the capsule is more spartan than what the ISS crowd wants in a capsule closer to the Zenit-launched 'Zarya' capsule that is much heavier. The Russians had an engine-equipped External Tank, which meant that their Buran style orbiters:<br>
<br>
1.) Could carry ten more tons than Columbia, since the engine- equipped External Tank known as Energia had the main engines<br>
<br>
2.) Had a tail compartment full of safer, live-weight-on-orbit kerosene and LOX maneuver propellants instead of a tail full of dead-weight/mass SSMEs which were useless once the ET was staged--forcing the use of high energy density--and highly toxic maneuver  propellants. These were placed in the OMS pods due to the SSMEs filling the whole aft boat-tail.<br>
<br>
3.) Could carry more propellant with no SSMEs in the way--and could carry yet more propellant in the rear payload bay to feed the smaller on-orbit only maneuver engines--due to the External Tank having the main cryogenic engines that fed from the hydrogen only found in the External Tank anyway.<br>
<br>
4.) Could be exchanged with 100 ton payload-pods. With the main hydrogen engines under the External Tank (Energia), the orbiter was a parasite that was merely along for the ride. This meant the External Tank did all the pushing, allowing for a safer, simpler orbiter to ride in a much more structually benign flight environment, as opposed to feeding hydrogen through holes or pass-throughs in its heat-shield while pushing the External Tank up while the orbiter-mount SSMEs were torque-ing and pushing up against the orbiter, as in Columbia.<br>
<br>
5.) Could be exchanged with hypersonic boilerplates, since a side-mount orbiter/payload position inflicts less pitch-loads and bending moments that top mounted vehicles--allowing for aerobrake disks and other outsized articles to be side-launched with less bending moments and less danger of pitch-over. An engine-equipped External Tank can one day be ringed with strap-ons like the SRBs, a dense circular upper stage added, and 200 tons can be taken to orbit as in the Energia/Vulkan iteration. Energia could have strap-ons added and removed--dialed up and back--allowing for a modular heavy-lifter to be budgeted and built over time.<br>
<br>
     Since our Columbia style orbiters have the main engines that feed of the External Tank's oxygen/hydrogen, you HAVE to fly the 90+ ton orbiter to carry the 20 ton only payloads. This at least gives you a stable platform, and EELVs can carry no more than that alone. A Delta IV with an OSP might run as much as $250 million a shot, with a program of $13 billion. This according to recent columns in SPACE NEWS.  <br>
<br>
     I have a piece I wish you to share with other members of The NASA ADVISORY COUNCIL. The guys in Marshall are the problem. And as much as it pains me to do so I would ask you to have Marshall get on the ball with a true Heavy-Lifter--or if they refuse--call for them to be shut down. My column reads as follows: <br>
<br>
     ************************************************* <br>
BEYOND THE DELTA IV--A FUTURE WITH TRUE HEAVY-LIFT<br>
<br>
                                      by<br>
<br>
                                Jeff Wright<br>
<br>
       With the demise of Columbia and her valiant crew, voices that were once shushed or drowned out have begun to make themselves heard. <br>
<br>
     Quietly, while fortunes were spent and lost, while X-33 and other unworkable confabulations were thrown together only to fall apart--the forces behind heavy-lift began to stir and make their presence known. No longer are they kept under the thumbs of SLI and other acronyms that can only spell &quot;failure&quot; by being two or more materials revolutions behind what is even remotely possible.<br>
<br>
     We who speak for heavy-lift have at last begun to shout.<br>
<br>
We know what works, for we have seen the successes that do in fact come from building big.<br>
<br>
     Institutions like NASA/Marshall, once known for building big rockets, now do everything but.<br>
<br>
     At last, things are beginning to change. Realizing the disaster that was X-33--how even the X-34 wasn't as cheap as people once thought it would be--the in-crowd have now at last been forced to swallow their pride in understanding that costs behind launch vehicles are largely inflexible and that small systems can be just as (if not more) costly to implement than larger systems, as shown by such pioneers as Bob Truax. That the Titan IV costs more than the Shuttle per launch is proof of that.<br>
<br>
     But have the powers-that-be really learned their lessons yet? The future of Heavy-Lift is about to be co-opted, even corrupted, from within.<br>
<br>
     When I think of Heavy-Lift, I think of 80-100 tons-to-orbit with the use of a large, simple, SINGLE hydrogen-filled External Tank fitted out with simple cryogenic engines like the RS-68, as I have called for in my other OPINION SPACE column 'Cut The Umbilical.'<br>
<br>
     Sadly those in charge have other ideas. <br>
<br>
     Many abuse the term &quot;heavy-lift.&quot;  The most flagrant dis-respect for the term came from those who would out-fit the overstretched Thor that we have come to call the Delta II 7925 with the solids developed for the luckless Delta III superstretch. The result is the mockery some would dare label the 'Delta II heavy.'<br>
<br>
     But most in the industry call the much more impressive Delta IV in its three Common-Core-Booster (CCB) configuration a heavy. I call it a medium, since it carries about the same as the Titan IV but never mind.<br>
<br>
     The problem is that a three-CCB (one CCB as the first stage and two as strap-on boosters) can only take around 20 tons or so to orbit.So if someone wanted to build a 100 ton structure in LEO (Low-Earth Orbit), you would have to launch FIVE of these 3-CCB launchers with each having an RS-68 engine apiece.<br>
<br>
     This means throwing away 15 of these $20 million dollar RS-68s in five launches of 3-CCB Delta IV heavies.<br>
<br>
     I have brought this troubling fact up to no avail in my dealings with certain higher-ups who have told me that there was talk of a Delta IV &quot;superheavy&quot; in the workes that may be called the DELTA V or the &quot;F-1&quot; after the Saturn V engine of the same name--even though it still uses the RS-68.<br>
<br>
     After placing a few calls and doing my homework (with more than a few heated 'discussions') I learned that this &quot;superheavy&quot; is in fact a Delta IV heavy with two more CCB (cores) as strap-ons. So you have one core as the first stage, two cores as strap-ons East-West and two more as strap-ons North-South--giving the stack a '+' sign look seen from above.<br>
<br>
     However, the payload has been estimated as only being 40 tons if that, opposed to the three-core Delta IV heavy's 20 tons.<br>
<br>
     There is a problem.<br>
<br>
     You see, if I launch three of these five-CCB &quot;superheavies&quot; to place 120 tons  in orbit, I STILL have to throw away 15 of those $20 million RS-68 engines! Whether you launch five 3-CCB Delta IV heavies or three 5-CCB Delta V &quot;superheavies,&quot; you throw 15 engines expensive engines away for every 100-120 tons in orbit.<br>
<br>
     And this doesn't include the costly upper stages.<br>
<br>
     Give me only three RS-68s underneath one large common External Tank with the existing SRBs and I will place 80-100 tons into orbit in only ONE LAUNCH!<br>
<br>
     My guess is that the folks at Boeing know this. The Delta V concept is probably a way to sell more engines in an attempt to gouge the taxpayer by winning some future NASA-unique mission contract. The problem is that such a program would be costly to us taxpayers and slow to implement due to multiple Delta launches--which will not excite space advocates and lead to such missions being limited or eliminated altogether.<br>
<br>
     Building space structures or spacecraft in such a piecemeal fashion using automation is risky at best. The stock Delta IV heavy is hardly better than the Titan IV. The Delta V &quot;superheavy&quot; concept is an awkward beast with a 40 ton payload that is too big for current commercial interests, yet is far too small for any new manned missions of any reach. Launch and assembly will be a very involved process that cannot excite the public any more than the ISS construction, itself being a 20 ton-at-a-time constuction due to the limitations of our current STS architecture.<br>
<br>
     So I have championed the three RS-68 powered External Tank concept using all-American design/parts that I call my Americanized Energia. Remembering that a rising tide floats all boats, the one large External Tank (ET) feeds three RS-68 engines, so that if one burns out, the others burn longer in its place--giving us engine-out capability which no Delta can offer, no matter how many strap-ons, since each CCB has one engine only--and the other CCBs cannot take over, being themselves independant. So over time, the likelihood of problems in another prolonged period of space assembly missions make for lower probabilities of success, leading to further cancellations and other NASA quagmires.<br>
<br>
      The RS-68 is a clean hydrogen engine, and will lead an inevitable push towards more environmentally friendly propellants. It has not been without problems, however. Problems with turbopumps and the like give an additional reason to have three feeding from one common External Tank, as opposed to several CCBs that are heavier in relation to the more limited amounts of hydrogen each CCB can hold. Hydrogen is a difficult fuel to work with, and keeping all the hydrogen in one tank simplifies fueling proceedures a great deal. This was true with that other engine-equipped External Tank called Energia, which could loft 100 ton automated pods or 80 ton Burans with 20 tons of cargo in the orbiter.( www.k26.com/buran ) This would have allowed speedier construction of space-stations stemming from larger modular designs. The ISS pieces (either STS or Proton-launched)are not more than 20 tons apiece, however--stretching delays even further. <br>
<br>
     The public is fed up with how ISS has dragged along, and will not put up with further delays. This will all limit Boeings sales in the long run. By placing the RS-68 engines underneath a large common External Tank (volume increases by the cube as surface area increases only by the square--making any increase in size modest)--very large structures of 100 tons or so can be placed into orbit in one launch, saving the taxpayer money while giving quicker, more visible results to keep interest and excitement alive.<br>
<br>
     This also means that if five launches of 100 ton pods to Low-Earth -Orbit can be had with five launch-per-year shuttle time tables that are quickened with the 100 ton pods being unmanned--you can have a 500 ton structure larger than ISS EVERY YEAR!<br>
<br>
     Boeing will have sold 15 of their RS-68s, and the 500 ton structures will still be cheaper than ISS due to fewer overall flights, which lesson risks. The public will be more interested, seeing visible progress--what with projects being assembled quickly being visible to the naked eye. No painful delays or problems stemming from premature aging of the first components that have outlived their limited lifespans by the time normal assembly is complete.<br>
<br>
     By having TRUE 80-100 ton-to-LEO heavy lift, the liklihood of public support for further space missions increases once progress is seen and citizens are wowed.<br>
<br>
     With the engine-equipped External Tank I detailed in my OPINION SPACE article, &quot;Cut The Umbilical&quot; <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.spacedaily.com/news/oped-03z.html">www.spacedaily.com/news/oped-03z.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> , you can launch 100 ton pods to serve like the defunct Columbus Free-Flyer independant station, where people can exercise without vibrations affecting other indepandant stations dedicated to mass-producing pharmaceuticals in bulk, as opposed to a thimbleful at a time on ISS while someone is trying to jog in place.<br>
<br>
     Thus my concept alone allows for true economies of scale--getting us away from the comsat mentalities of  the small minded groups who now dominate space. <br>
<br>
     My detractors say there are no current 100 ton payloads. I say there are no 40 ton payloads either. They say my concept needs a new pad.<br>
<br>
So will the Delta V, especially if it carries an OSP atop it.<br>
<br>
<br>
     The Russians pulled ahead of us by making launchers more powerful than needed, giving them an advantage over time as satellites kept getting larger (See my column here: <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://groups.yahoo.com/group/inside_ksc/message/6932">groups.yahoo.com/group/in...ssage/6932</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> )<br>
<br>
In fact, Russian launchers were more space-boosters that became ICBMs than the other way around. Our ability to shrink circuits allowed us to get away with smaller vehicles, but as more people on Earth began to have more and newer chips--as more people began to demand more information--the comsats had to bulk up to keep up. This trend can only worsen with digital battlefields and radarsats. By the time we in the United States finally built our first non ICBM-based launcher in over 20 years, the market fell out due to the glut of Soviet-based vehicles built decades ago--back when the small-minded were saying &quot;there are no payloads for heavy lift.&quot;   <br>
<br>
Will we believe this old lie? Or will we press on for a better tomorrow?  <br>
