I read BACK TO THE MOON recently and I think that Jim Baker's plan which Homar Hickam fleshed out in his novel is perhaps more workable than even he could have imagined. <br>
<br>
More on that in a moment... <br>
<br>
   I have had a bit of a love/hate relationship with the shuttle in recent years. When I read SPACEFLIGHT IN THE ERA OF AEROSPACE PLANES I learned to hate the shuttle after I understood that despite its complexity, it was merely a compromise design. <br>
<br>
     But after the X-33 burst its tanks ON THE GROUND, I understood just how lucky we are to even have a shuttle of any kind that can lift, service, and RETURN payloads of any real size. <br>
<br>
     Hydrogen-based launch vehicles, especially the SSTO's, were all the rage until people understood that these things are little more than eggshells--supersized composite dirigibles that have to survive re-entry at hypersonic speeds. The Hindenburg had a better chance doing that than X-33--at least it actually got off the ground. <br>
<br>
<br>
     That's why I finally came back to the shuttle, my head hung in shame like that of a philandering husband crawling back to his wife, his trysts having been exposed. <br>
<br>
     One of the things Homer wrote about in his novel was the possibility of using ETs as space station modules, as per Gene Meyers (and others) whom I have written to in the past. It is, after all, easier to leave an ET in orbit with equipment for a space station than it would be to put wings on it, landing gear in it, and a heat shield under it--and call it an RLV, which, to save weight, would resemble an eggshell.<br>
<br>
In other words, you would have the X-33. <br>
<br>
All Skunk, No Works.<br>
<br>
<br>
But enough on spacecraft that look like cough drops. <br>
<br>
For some years now, I have been aware of the growing nostalgia for the Saturn V--I have even contributed to same. But such a vehicle would have few uses and would require extensive re-tooling and launch-pad/tower modifications. <br>
<br>
But this philandering husband has had enough of &quot;older women&quot; which would truly be &quot;high maintainence babe's.&quot; <br>
<br>
No more affairs.<br>
<br>
I have seen Jenny Jones enough times to understand that when one's wife is down and out, she doesn't need abandoning--she just needs a makeover.<br>
<br>
That is what our shuttle needs--a makeover.<br>
<br>
True, it will be major with a lot of liposuction (no SSME's on the orbiter--put RS-68's on the ET for a Mars booster)...and we have to get rid of the nasty &quot;free radicals&quot; (no hydrazine poison--go to LOX/kerosene as in the BURAN)...then there is that eventual hip replacement (no SRB's--have, one day, LOX/kerosene motors like the Energia's RD-170, 174 and LockMart's RD-180, but with four chambers). <br>
<br>
<br>
Behold, our lady has a new lease on life. She can launch our BURAN-style parasite orbiter or a Mars ship just as easily--no Shuttle-C on her back. <br>
<br>
It is an American Energia, not the Saturn V, that we must have. With the failure of the X-33, with the shuttle replacement crowd fighting with the Mars exploration crowd--we need a unifying factor. An Energia type STS would fit the bill. SSTOs seem farther away now than they ever did--and they are not always needed. Every pound of weight brought back from orbit is one pound less of payload. <br>
<br>
     Magnum style launchers will be good for moderately heavy payloads, but are good for nothing else. I say that we keep the lateral payload mount and a metal ET that would be stretched and modified to where it would lend itself to space station construction more easily--making for modules so darn big not even Hickam's MOONDOG could orbit them. <br>
<br>
     An Energia-ed STS would have its own avionics as in the Energia, making the orbiter just another payload that would have its own avionics as well. The booster stack is thus independant and the orbiter would be lighter and simpler. With the main engines on the tank, the orbiter would not be a load bearing structure as soon as the boosters fall away at separation time. <br>
<br>
       The Buran was simpler and had better loiter capability with kerosene for fuel in its tanks that were placed where our dead-weight-on-orbit SSME's are. Small jets could be placed on a similar Americanized Buran-type shuttle. These would ignite after re-entry so the orbiter would have some power if the stack had to be dropped or upon return. It would no longer be a true glider, though its jets would not have to be able to lift the orbiter once it was on the ground, though it could be unloaded, be refueled and with strap-on jets could fly back to Florida to be mated to another STS/ENERGIA that could also be used for Mars launches.<br>
<br>
<br>
And the current Shuttles could be outfitted like COLUMBIA was in your novel, BACK TO THE MOON. The old fleet could be given new life this way, with the propellant fittings mated to a tank in the payload bay. The current RCS &quot;bulges&quot; would remain as they are compact and already there. The ETs left behind as space stations on each flight--be it Mars ship, shuttle, etc.<br>
<br>
<br>
The STS/Energia would therefore be like the B-52 and could sereve us for many years while dropping simpler payloads for future RLV's. The booster stack would still have a place even then, being circled with strap-ons and serving as the first stage for even larger stations of the future, or serveing as a hub for an ET-based station.<br>
<br>
And all this without scramjets, composite LH2 tanks, or aerospikes. <br>
I think that my plan may be the only way for us to have a simpler conventional Shuttle--have a Mars booster--and for you to make Jim Baker's plan a reality. A movie of BACK TO THE MOON could help fund this way to bring competing interests together and get things done while we are still alive. Business is going to get into space in a BIG way--but not yet. They need a big push that only you may be able to give. Many who favor an all private route and who don't want to dirty their hands with government money forget their own saw--there is no &quot;government money.&quot; <br>
<br>
It's ours--either we spend it or they do. <br>
The technophobes--the JANISTS as Hickham called call them-- are here even now. From Art Bell to Ralph Nader to Earth First! to UNABOMBER--they will not stop until they have cut off our opposible thumbs and given humanity a collective lobotomy so they can put us back into the caves with Alley Oop or back in the trees with Tarzan and Jeremy Rifkin. We either give our kids the stars--or they will have the dirt instead. That was not what was meant by the meek inheriting the Earth--for eco-terrorists are far from meek. They exist too. <br>
<br>
Who can stop them?<br>
<br>
 We, Happy Few. <br>
<br>
But we must build up our forces. <br>
Infrastructure before innovation.  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=publiusr@nuclearspace>publiusr</A> at: 3/28/03 2:53:55 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 402<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/1/03 2:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=320.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   OK with the HLV talk, but nonsense about the OSP</span><hr size=1> I agree that the Buran is a better system than the STS. I always liked the engine-less plane, expendable but cheap &amp; reliable engines, and easy Shuttle-C type modifiaction.<br>
