<br>
Yes, there's nothing which can help you in a worst-case situation except to not be there. That's not to stop us from building the best system possible (which is not in any way at all the Shutle orbiter) and accepting reasonable risk.<br>
Make the best fantasy technology solutions you want to speculate about, and I'll pick it apart with worst-case&quot; situations. A meaningless nit-picking exercise.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; Small spaceplanes are just too vulnerable to weight creep.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Ex: the French/ESA Hermes. The STS obiter is an example of this, and not for small planes alone.<br>
On the other end of he spectrum is the HL-20. Do not try to do everything with it, don't add cargo. Make it a special-purpose plane for getting people up &amp; down safely. No many-day's life support with EVA prep and all the extra crap you'd want to add to a wish-mobile.<br>
(BTW, I consider Bono &amp; Truax to be a little above the crowd of &quot;pundits&quot; when they say don't mix crew &amp; cargo. Cite &quot;weight-creep all you want, but I fail to see how the HL-20 design philosophy could go above the throw-weight of the new crop of medium-heavy ELVs coming up today)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; I would only ignite a nuke in space, so as to not alarm too many of the anti-nukes out there.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I've said the same many times (don't know why this came up here...). Personally, I don't give a hoot about the anti's who won't unbend at all. Give them a platform to say that there's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>no moral difference</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> between enjoying looking at photos of a new planet from a nuke powered probe, and getting your rocks off watching a PGM hit an Iraqi bunker, and they'll marginalize themselves out of exisence.<br>
<br>
 I don't like the idea of dropping a nuke powered rover into a possibly life-bearing ocean with no provision for retrieval, but I love the idea of a huge Jupiter mission on a big Orion ship (possibly even ground-launched, if it can be done cleanly), with a big nuclear sub for Europa.<br>
The staunch antis I'll allow to chain themselves to the launch towers in protest. Maybe design it so their body masses might provide some extra propellant mass to the first couple of clean sub-KT bomb shots...<br>
<br>
Otherwise, I'm all for a space-use NPR fleet. No possible reasonable objection to a good responsible program, and I'll debate that with anybody -Gagnon, Kaku, etc.<br>
<br>
The benefit of Shuttle-C is that the entire launch infrastructure at present for the STS can be used tomorrow, with zero modifications. Rotating Service Structure, VAB, Flame Trenches, existing ETs, everything as-is.<br>
 Try to get NASA to modify the ETs for vertical payload integration, and they'll give you a bill of $10B a year for 10 years for studies, with several hundred Bs for launch pad modifications added later. At last with Shutte-C we can bludgeon them with something simpler &amp; cheaper than what's presently used, instead of more complexity.<br>
<br>
